Data Description:¶

The data is related with direct marketing campaigns of a Portuguese banking institution. The marketing campaigns were based on phone calls. Often, more than one contact to the same client was required, in order to access if the product (bank term deposit) would be ('yes') or not ('no') subscribed.

Domain:¶

Banking

Context:¶

Leveraging customer information is paramount for most businesses. In the case of a bank, attributes of customers like the ones mentioned below can be crucial in strategizing a marketing campaign when launching a new product.

Attribute Information:¶

  1. age (numeric)
  2. job : type of job (categorical: 'admin.','blue-collar','entrepreneur','housemaid','management','retired','self-employed','services','student','technician','unemployed','unknown')
  3. marital : marital status (categorical: 'divorced','married','single','unknown'; note: 'divorced' means divorced or widowed)
  4. education (categorical: 'basic.4y','basic.6y','basic.9y','high.school','illiterate','professional.course','university.degree','unknown')
  5. default: has credit in default? (categorical: 'no','yes','unknown')
  6. balance: average yearly balance, in euros (numeric)
  7. housing: has housing loan? (categorical: 'no','yes','unknown')
  8. loan: has personal loan? (categorical: 'no','yes','unknown')
  9. contact: contact communication type (categorical: 'cellular','telephone')
  10. day: last contact day of the month (numeric 1 -31)
  11. month: last contact month of year (categorical: 'jan', 'feb', 'mar', ..., 'nov', 'dec')
  12. duration: last contact duration, in seconds (numeric). Important note: this attribute highly affects the output target (e.g., if duration=0 then y='no'). Yet, the duration is not known before a call is performed. Also, after the end of the call y is obviously known. Thus, this input should only be included for benchmark purposes and should be discarded if the intention is to have a realistic predictive model.
  13. campaign: number of contacts performed during this campaign and for this client (numeric, includes last contact)
  14. pdays: number of days that passed by after the client was last contacted from a previous campaign (numeric; 999 means client was not previously contacted)
  15. previous: number of contacts performed before this campaign and for this client (numeric)
  16. poutcome: outcome of the previous marketing campaign (categorical: 'failure','nonexistent','success')
  17. target: has the client subscribed a term deposit? (binary: "yes","no")

Learning Outcomes:¶

 Exploratory Data Analysis
 Preparing the data to train a model
 Training and making predictions using an Ensemble Model
 Tuning an Ensemble model

Objective:¶

The classification goal is to predict if the client will subscribe (yes/no) a term deposit (variable y).

def numerical_feature_plot(feature):
    fig,ax=plt.subplots(nrows=1,ncols=2,figsize=(14,6))
    sns.distplot(df[feature],ax=ax[0])
    ax[0].set_title("Histogram of "+feature)
    sns.boxplot(y=df[feature],ax=ax[1])
    ax[1].set_title("Boxplot of "+feature)
In [12]:
def numerical_feature_analysis(feature):
    feature_min=df[feature].min()
    feature_max=df[feature].max()
    feature_q1=np.quantile(df[feature],0.25)
    feature_q3=np.quantile(df[feature],0.75)
    feature_IQR=(feature_q3-feature_q1)
    feature_lower_whisker=feature_q1-(feature_IQR*1.5)
    feature_upper_whisker=feature_q3+(feature_IQR*1.5)

    print("Feature: ",feature)
    if (feature_lower_whisker<feature_min) and (feature_upper_whisker>feature_max):
        print("No outliers.")
    else:
        if (feature_upper_whisker<feature_max):
            print("Outliers are present in maximum. ",feature," above ",round(feature_upper_whisker,2)," are outliers and total are ",df[df[feature]>feature_upper_whisker][feature].count())
        if (feature_lower_whisker>feature_min):
            print("Outliers are present in minimum. ",feature," below ",round(feature_lower_whisker,2)," are outliers and total are ",df[df[feature]<feature_lower_whisker][feature].count())
    
    print("----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------")

# Function for creating count plot and the corresponding percentage distribution plots for categorical variables
# Count plot is to help in understanding the distribution of the feature
# % distribution plot helps us to see the % distribution of different categories for a feature.
def categorical_feature_plot(feature):
    fig,ax=plt.subplots(nrows=1,ncols=2,figsize=(14,6))
    df[feature].value_counts().plot(kind='bar',ax=ax[0],rot=90,title="Counts of "+feature)
    ax[0].set_xlabel(feature)
    #sns.countplot(df[feature],ax=ax[0],order=df[feature].unique())
    #ax[0].set_title("Counts of "+feature)
    #ax[0].set_xticklabels(df[feature].unique(), rotation=90)
    df[feature].value_counts(normalize=True).plot(kind='bar',ax=ax[1])
    ax[1].set_title("Distribution of "+feature)
    ax[1].set_xlabel(feature)
    ax[1].set_ylabel("% Distribution")
    ax[1].set_xticklabels(df[feature].value_counts(normalize=True).index, rotation=90)

Observations:

job: Data is not uniformly distributed across jobs. 20+ % each of customers belong to blue-collar and management.

marital: 60% of the customers are married followed by single and divorced.

education: More than 50% of the customers have completed secondary education.

default: Most of the customer have credit default as NO. This feature may not be of useful in prediction models as the variance is very low.

housing: Good distribution is there between for this feature. 55% has housing loan and 45% didn't.

loan: 16% has taken personal loan and rest didnt have.

contact: Most of the customers are contacted through cellular (64%). Through telephone its only 6.4% and rest[29%] of the customer contact is Unknown.

day: Most of the customers are last contacted for the present campaign between month days 17 and 21. However customers are contacted less on 1st day of month.

month: 30% of the customers are last contacted in May month followed by June[15%] and August[14%]. However in december month, customers are last contacted less.

campaign: 75% of data lies within value 3. Right Skewed.

previous: More than 80% of the data has value 0. This indicates that most of the customers are not contacted before this campaign and is in align with our assumption on pdays feature.

poutcome: Outcome is Unknown for 82% of the data. 11% of data is failure and only 3.3% of data is success. Since for most of the data Outcome is Unknown, in real life this feature may not be useful.

Target: 88% of the customers didnt take Term Deposit. Only 12% have opted for TD. Here also distribution is not good enough to get better predictions for customers who will opt for Term Deposit.

def feature_target_plot(feature):

def feature_target_analysis(feature,count):
    if feature!='Target':
        plt.figure(count,figsize=(8,6))
        if i in numerical_feature_list:
            nbins=(df[feature].max()-abs(df[feature].min()))/(np.std(df[feature]))
            new_feature=feature+'_Band'
            df[new_feature]=pd.qcut(x=df[feature],q=4,duplicates='drop')
            feature=new_feature
            feature_band_list.append(new_feature)
            sns.pointplot(x=feature,y='Target',data=df[['Target',feature]].groupby(by=feature,as_index=False).mean())
            plt.xticks(rotation=90)
        else:
            sns.pointplot(x=feature,y='Target',data=df[['Target',feature]].groupby(by=feature,as_index=False).mean())
            plt.xticks(rotation=90)

Outliers Treatment¶

As per all the above analysis, Outliers are present for below numerical features:

Feature: age
Outliers are present in maximum. age above 70.5 are outliers and total are 487

Decision: By observing the above bivariate analysis performed between "age_Band vs Target", its clear that from age 40+ onwards there is an upward trend for TD opting. The same trend has been followed in outliers as well. Hence these outliers shouldnt be an impact in predicting the Target. Lets keep it. And inorder to reduce the high values of outliers, we can do binning.

Binning¶

In [45]:
from collections import defaultdict
In [46]:
# To convert less frequent occuring categories and grouping them as 'others'.
# uq_dict can help in saving the unique values which can be used for any upcoming new data
uq_dict=dict()
f_uq_cat_list=[]

for i in df.select_dtypes(include='object').columns:
    if i!='Target':
        if df[i].nunique()>4:
            dfv=df[i].value_counts(normalize=True)
            f_uq_cat_list=list(dfv.loc[(dfv>0.10)].index)
            if type(df.loc[0,i])==str:
                default='others'
            else:
                default=9999
            d=defaultdict(lambda: default)
            d.update({i:i for i in f_uq_cat_list})
            uq_dict[i]=dict(d)
            df[i]=df[i].map(d)
            df[i]=df[i].astype('object')

Approach¶

Below approach is followed in data prepartion:

  1. Scale the continuous variables.

  2. One hot encoding FIT for Categorical variables.

  3. Split the dataset into train and test.

  4. Use SMOTENC to generate synthetic data for Continuous and categorical features together.

  5. One hot encoding TRANSFORMATION for train and test dataset.

Note: Above approach is followed to generate better synthetic data. If onehot transform is done before smotting then because of data sparsity(more columns) the synthetic data generated is not that great for models.

Metrics¶

Since its a imbalanced classification and even after smotting the minority class is only 35% of majority class. So metrics like accuracy are not helpful to select the best model. Below metrics are considered for this use case:

  1. AUC - Can help in selecting optimal threshold where maximum difference between TPR and FPR
  2. Recall score - Can help in selecting model where False Negatives are less.
    False Negatives for minority class (Term Deposit Opting) means the customers want to opt for TD but our model predicted they are not in favor.
  3. f1 score - Finally f1-score help in balancing both precision and recall.
    If we consider just recall score then there is a high chance that we end up with low precision.
    Lower precision would create more false positives which is an unnecessary burden on Customer service team.
In [103]:
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score,confusion_matrix,classification_report,recall_score,f1_score,auc,roc_auc_score,roc_curve
from sklearn.preprocessing import binarize
In [105]:
# Store performance of each model in this list
model_results=[]

# Creating a function which gives accuracy, recall, f1-score,AUC and optimal threshold values for a model
def model_pred_acc_auc(model,base_model=None):
    ytest_pred=model.predict(X_test)
    train_acc=accuracy_score(y_train,model.predict(X_train))
    test_acc=accuracy_score(y_test,ytest_pred)
    test_recall_score=recall_score(y_test,ytest_pred)
    test_f1_score=f1_score(y_test,ytest_pred)
    ytrain_pred_proba=model.predict_proba(X_train)[:,1]
    ytest_pred_proba=model.predict_proba(X_test)[:,1]
    fpr, tpr, thresholds = roc_curve(y_train, ytrain_pred_proba)
    th_df=pd.DataFrame({'FPR':fpr,'TPR':tpr,'TH':thresholds})
    idx=np.argmax(th_df['TPR']-th_df['FPR'])
    opt_th=th_df.iloc[idx]['TH']
    ytest_pred = binarize([ytest_pred_proba], opt_th)[0]
    test_f1_score_opt_th=f1_score(y_test,ytest_pred)
    test_recall_score_opt_th=recall_score(y_test,ytest_pred)
    test_acc_opt_th=accuracy_score(y_test,ytest_pred)
    train_auc=auc(fpr,tpr)
    test_auc=roc_auc_score(y_test,ytest_pred_proba)

    print("Training data accuracy before threshold change: ",train_acc)
    print("Testing data accuracy before threshold change: ",test_acc)
    print("Testing data Recall score before threshold change: ",test_recall_score)
    print("Testing data f1-score before threshold change: ",test_f1_score)
    print("Training data AUC: ",train_auc)
    print("Testing data AUC: ",test_auc)
    print("Optimal threshold is: ", opt_th )
    print("Testing data accuracy after threshold change: ",test_acc_opt_th)
    print("Testing data Recall score after threshold change: ",test_recall_score_opt_th)
    print("Testing data f1-score after threshold change: ",test_f1_score_opt_th)

    if base_model is None:
        model_results.append({model.__class__.__name__:[np.round(train_acc,4),
                                                        np.round(test_acc,4),
                                                        np.round(test_recall_score,4),
                                                        np.round(test_f1_score,4),
                                                        np.round(train_auc,4),
                                                        np.round(test_auc,4),
                                                        np.round(opt_th,4),
                                                        np.round(test_acc_opt_th,4),
                                                        np.round(test_recall_score_opt_th,4),
                                                        np.round(test_f1_score_opt_th,4)]})
    else:
        model_results.append({base_model.__class__.__name__+'-'+model.__class__.__name__:[np.round(train_acc,4),
                                                        np.round(test_acc,4),
                                                        np.round(test_recall_score,4),
                                                        np.round(test_f1_score,4),
                                                        np.round(train_auc,4),
                                                        np.round(test_auc,4),
                                                        np.round(opt_th,4),
                                                        np.round(test_acc_opt_th,4),
                                                        np.round(test_recall_score_opt_th,4),
                                                        np.round(test_f1_score_opt_th,4)]})
    return ytest_pred

Notations:¶


BFR_TH_TRAIN_ACC - Before Threshold Change Training Accuracy
BFR_TH_TEST_ACC - Before Threshold Change Testing Accuracy
BFR_TH_RECALL_SCORE - Before Threshold Change Recall score
BFR_TH_F1_SCORE - Before Threshold Change f1-score
TRAIN_AUC - Training data AUC
TEST_AUC - Testing AUC
OPT_TH - Optimal Threshold value at which maximum difference is present between TPR and FPR
AFT_TH_TEST_ACC - After Threshold change Test Accuracy
AFT_TH_RECALL_SCORE - After Threshold change Recall score
AFT_TH_F1_SCORE - After Threshold change f1-score

Model with highest  AFT_TH_TEST_ACC  is :  KNeighborsClassifier  & its value is:  0.7703
Model with highest  TEST_AUC  is :  LogisticRegression  & its value is:  0.735
Model with highest  AFT_TH_RECALL_SCORE  is :  GaussianNB  & its value is:  0.6541
Model with highest  AFT_TH_F1_SCORE  is :  LogisticRegression  & its value is:  0.3411

Final Decision:¶

Though KNN has highest accuracy, its AUC and f1-score are low compared to others. On a overall, taking AUC and f1-score into consideration, Logistic Regression is better compared to all. Because here, Logistic Regression has maintained all the metrics in equal priority. So its the first choice out of all base models.

        bgc_max_features_dict[i.__class__.__name__]=bgc_gscv_df[bgc_gscv_df['param_base_estimator']==i].sort_values(by='rank_test_score')['param_max_features'].iloc[0]

# Getting the best params of Ada Boost Classifers for each base model. Here there are two params: n_estimator and learning_rate

ada_n_estimator_dict={}
ada_learning_rate_dict={}

for i in ada_gscv_df['param_base_estimator'].unique():
    if i is None:
        ada_n_estimator_dict['DecisionTreeClassifier']=ada_gscv_df[ada_gscv_df['param_base_estimator'].isna()].sort_values(by='rank_test_score')['param_n_estimators'].iloc[0]
        ada_learning_rate_dict['DecisionTreeClassifier']=ada_gscv_df[ada_gscv_df['param_base_estimator'].isna()].sort_values(by='rank_test_score')['param_learning_rate'].iloc[0]
    else:
        ada_n_estimator_dict[i.__class__.__name__]=ada_gscv_df[ada_gscv_df['param_base_estimator']==i].sort_values(by='rank_test_score')['param_n_estimators'].iloc[0]
        ada_learning_rate_dict[i.__class__.__name__]=ada_gscv_df[ada_gscv_df['param_base_estimator']==i].sort_values(by='rank_test_score')['param_learning_rate'].iloc[0]
        
print(ada_n_estimator_dict)
print(ada_learning_rate_dict)

{'LogisticRegression': 500, 'GaussianNB': 100, 'DecisionTreeClassifier': 500}
{'LogisticRegression': 0.5, 'GaussianNB': 0.5, 'DecisionTreeClassifier': 0.5}

Conclusion¶

By looking at above, I prefer to use LogisticRegression-BaggingClassifier.
Reason being, it has reasonable AUC and f1-score. And along with these, it has high recall score which can help in reducing False Negatives.
Second choice would be XGBoost because of its high f1-score and has good AUC score too.
Though KNN has been in top 5 in many metrices, I wouldnt prefer it because of its low recall score.
